# LoadZone Core

- LoadZone is a monorepo for amateur football wellness monitoring with two main apps:
  `apps/app` for staff/admin and `apps/player` for player check-ins.
- Always use `pnpm` and prefer package-level commands when working inside one app or package.
- Reuse existing packages before adding code:
  `@repo/design-system`, `@repo/database`, `@repo/auth`, `@repo/ai`.
- Keep changes minimal and focused.
- Use strict TypeScript with explicit parameter and return types. Avoid `any`.
- Prefer `unknown`, type guards, or `satisfies` over unsafe `as` casts.
- Prefer `@repo/*` imports for shared packages and `@/` for local app imports.
- Check whether a shared UI primitive already exists in `packages/design-system/components/ui`
  before creating a new component.
- Do not run builds by default. In Next.js work, only run build/dev commands if the user asks.
- Add or update docs when they prevent repeated prompt context, clarify project conventions,
  or support future agent work. **Language:** write repo docs, PRDs, ADRs, and `CONTEXT.md`
  updates in **English**; product UI copy in **Spanish**; see [`AGENTS.md`](../../AGENTS.md)
  (*Language convention*) for grill sessions (Spanish questions OK, persisted answers in English).
- Add or update tests when the change touches business rules, input validation, regressions,
  or bug fixes. Skip low-value tests that only restate the implementation.
- If a contract is used by only one feature, keep it local to that feature. Promote it to a
  shared package only when it is consumed by at least two real boundaries.
- Domain vocabulary and entity relationships: see root [`CONTEXT.md`](../../CONTEXT.md).
- Never expose or log player tokens. Treat public player flows as security-sensitive.
